1. DIRECTORY MANAGEMENT COMMANDS
i) mkdir
Creates a new directory.
mkdir name of the directory
ii) chdir / cd
Changes the current working directory.
cd name of the directory
iii) ls
Lists files and directories.
ls -l
iv)rmdir
remove directory
rmdir directory name
2. FILE MANAGEMENT COMMANDS
i)	touch
Create empty file
touch file name
ii)	echo
Write content into file
echo “hello friend”>file name
iii)	cat
Displays file contents.
cat filename
iv)	mv
Copy file content into other file
mv file1 file 2
v)	chmod
Changes file permissions.
chmod 755 file name 
To check weather permission is apply or not write following command 
ls -l filename 
vi)	chown
Changes file owner.
chown user filename 
E.g chown codeuser10003 trial
vii)chgrp
Changes file group.
chgrp group filename 

3. PROCESS MANAGEMENT COMMANDS
i) ps
Displays running processes.
ps -ef
ii) top
Displays real-time running processes and system resource usage such as CPU and memory.
top
iii) kill 
The kill command is used to terminate a running process using its process ID (PID).
kill pid (e.g kill 1234)
iv) killall
Terminates all processes with a given name.
killall process_name
E.g killall 
4. TEXT PROCESSING COMMANDS
sort
Sorts lines of a file.	
sort data.txt
grep
Searches for a pattern in a file.
grep "Linux" notes.txt
awk
Processes and extracts text.
awk '{print $1}' file.txt

5. FILE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM CALLS
open()
Opens or creates a file.
read()
Reads data from a file.
write()
Writes data to a file.
close()
Closes an opened file.

6. PROCESS & USER INFORMATION SYSTEM CALLS
getpid()
Returns process ID of calling process.
getuid() / geteuid()
Returns real and effective user ID.
getgid() / getegid()
Returns real and effective group ID.
